@node "Introduction" "Introduction   "

 This  program  is  a  useful tool for developers, bored with going through
 tons of bug reports, received in e-mails, on paper and in other, sometimes
 very  strange,  forms.  Thanks to Bug Reporter you dont have to think what
 was  written  here  and  there  and  what  author wanted to say with these
 curious  signs...   Now  you  can  easily  manage bug reports from various
 testers in a standarized form, which greatly enhances the speed of fixing
 these  bugs  and  shortens the development time of the whole project.  Bug
 Reporter  lets  you  better  organize  work  on the project, which is very
 important  in  these  days...   Perhaps  I  should  name  this program Bug
 Organizer...:)

 This  is  the  evaluation  version  of  Bug  Reporter.  There are only two
 differences  between  full  registered  version  and  this  version.  Full
 version has sorting enabled and saves all messages, not only one report.
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features       "

                               @{b}Key Features@{ub}

 - Simple,  intuitive  way  of creating bug reports for any kind of tested
   application.
 - Detailed description of each bug allows easy fixing.

 - Sorting by various criteria, including type, date and priority.

 - Support for e-mailing bug reports over Internet.

 - Built-it text editor for fast editing bug descriptions.

 - Merging several reports into one allows working with several testers.

 - Multiplatform tool with data compatibility.

 - Overall, very useful utility for every developer around :)
@endnode

@node "SystemRequirements" "Requirements   "

                        @{b} System requirements@{ub}

 Bug  Reporter  requires an Amiga with operating system 2.04 (V37) or above
 and   reqtools.library  to  run.   All  memory  requirements  are  handled
 dynamically,  so  you  are  able  to use it even if you are low on memory.
 Hard disk is not required.

 Bug  Reporter  also  uses one of TCP/IP stacks, available for Amigas like
 AmiTCP or Miami.
@endnode

@node "Instalation" "Installation   "

                            @{b} Installation@{ub}

 There  is  no  installation  script  for  Bug Reporter supplied right now,
 sorry.   This  release  can be installed so easily on your system that you
 should  be able to perform that task manually.  If not, you're not advised
 to use Bug Reporter anyway.

 Copy  BugReporter  and BugReporter.info to any location on your hard drive
 or disk.  If not already present, copy reqtools.library into your sys:libs
 drawer.

 After these steps, Bug Reporter can be started via Shell or Workbench.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage          "

                               @{b} Usage@{ub}
 
